# Accessibility and Responsive Design

## Accessibility first

- Use semantic HTML: `header`, `main`, `section`, `article`, `nav`, `footer`.
- Provide accessible names: `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, and meaningful link text.
- Ensure interactive elements are keyboard reachable and have visible focus states.
- Do not remove existing ARIA attributes when refactoring components.
- Prefer real buttons and links over clickable divs.

## Responsive first and mobile parity

- Design and verify at desktop, tablet, and mobile breakpoints.
- Preserve existing breakpoints and layout behavior in `app/globals.css`.
- Mobile must receive the same content and hierarchy as desktop — not a reduced experience.
- Test narrow widths (≤640px) and mid widths (≤1000px) before shipping UI changes.

## CSS changes

- Extend existing design tokens (`:root` variables) instead of introducing one-off colors.
- Keep the fixed `.world` background layer intact behind all content.
- Avoid changes that break `backdrop-filter`, grid proportions, or glass card styling.
